comment_text:
Cow in Hinduism:

Eat beef (Cow Mata) allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) declares: "On the occasion of the marriage of a girl, oxen and cows are sacrificed".
Rigveda (06/17/1) states that "Indra used to eat beef, veal, horse and buffalo."
Manusmriti (Chapter 5 / Verse 30) says: "It is not sinful to eat the flesh of edible animals, because Brahma has created both the eaters and the edibles."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahmin (1/1/2/21) that, "I eat meat because it is very soft and delicious".
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow must be sacrificed upon the arrival of a guest, on the occasion of 'Shraddha' of ancestors and on the occasion of a marriage."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes: "If a Brahmin refuses to eat the meat that is offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."
